17.1: Simple linear regression

Introduction

This is code for Section 17.1 of Kruschke using a normal noise distribution. Make sure that the two files WtHtData30.csv and WtHtData300.csv are in your project directory.

Preliminaries

Load necessary packages:

library(tidyverse)
library(rstan)
library(shinystan)
library(bayesplot)

Set Stan to save compiled code.

rstan_options(auto_write = TRUE)

Set Stan to use parallel processing where possible.

options(mc.cores = parallel::detectCores())

WtHtData300

Well also be interested in comparing the results of using the raw data versus mean-centering the x variable. (Kruschke standardizes both variables using z-scores, but that makes the coefficients of the model harder to interpret.)

x30_mc <- WtHtData30$height - mean(WtHtData30$height)
x300_mc <- WtHtData300$height - mean(WtHtData300$height)

Were going to run three different examples, so well make three lists.

N30 <- NROW(WtHtData30)
x30 <- WtHtData30$height
y30 <- WtHtData30$weight
stan_data_30 <- list(N = N30, x = x30, y = y30)
stan_data_30_mc <- list(N = N30, x = x30_mc, y = y30)
N300 <- NROW(WtHtData300)
y300 <- WtHtData300$weight
stan_data_300_mc <- list(N = N300, x = x300_mc, y = y300)

Stan code

We set normal priors on the \(\beta_{0}\) (intercept) and \(\beta_{1}\) parameters centered at reasonable values and spread over a wide range. The normal model for the likelihood is centered at mu, but mu is really a vector of values that represent the mean y value for each value of x, which is a point that lies on our regression line, hence the code in the transformed parameters block:

mu = beta0 + beta1 * x;
data {
    int<lower = 0> N;
    vector[N] x;
    vector<lower = 0>[N] y;
}
transformed data {
    real<lower = 0> M0;
    real<lower = 0> S0;
    real<lower = 0> M1;
    real<lower = 0> S1;
    real<lower = 0> L;
    real<lower = 0> H;
    
    M0 = 70;
    S0 = 70;
    M1 = 0;
    S1 = 3;
    L = 0;
    H = 1000;
}
parameters {
    real beta0;
    real beta1;
    real<lower = 0> sigma;
}
transformed parameters {
    vector<lower = 0>[N] mu;
    
    mu = beta0 + beta1 * x;
}
model {
    beta0 ~ normal(M0, S0);
    beta1 ~ normal(M1, S1);
    sigma ~ uniform(L, H);
    y ~ normal(mu, sigma);
}
generated quantities {
    real y_rep[N];
    
    for (n in 1:N) {
        y_rep[n] = normal_rng(mu[n], sigma);
    }
}

Sampling from the model

set.seed(11111)
fit_WtHt30 <- sampling(WtHt, data = stan_data_30, refresh = 0)

Diagnosing the model

plot(fit_WtHt30, plotfun = "ac", pars = c("beta0", "beta1", "sigma"))

plot(fit_WtHt30, plotfun = "trace",
     pars = c("beta0", "beta1", "sigma"))

The huge range on the intercept is due to the fact that small changes to the slope way out to the right of the graph will result in lines that meet the y-axis in wildly different places. This is a good reason to standardize (or at least mean-center the data).

The mean-centered model

set.seed(11111)
fit_WtHt30_mc <- sampling(WtHt, data = stan_data_30_mc, refresh = 0)

Much better diagnostic plots:

Posterior predictive check

Well just do this for the example with 30 observations.

y <- y30

Extract predicted values:

samples_WtHt30 <- extract(fit_WtHt30)
y_rep <- samples_WtHt30$y_rep
ppc_hist(y, y_rep[1:5, ])

ppc_boxplot(y, y_rep[1:5, ])

ppc_dens(y, y_rep[1:5, ])

ppc_dens_overlay(y, y_rep[1:30, ])

ppc_stat_2d(y, y_rep)
